## Model Fitting & Interpretation 



<div class='question-begin'>Question 4</div><div class='question-body'>



Consider that Neuroticism has already been $z$-scored, but scs has not. To ensure that we can compare the effects of our estimates (and so they are both on meaningful scales), standardize the scs variable.

:::{.callout-tip appearance="simple" collapse="true"}

### Hint

Review the [standardisation flashcards](https://uoepsy.github.io/dapr2/2526/labs/1_b3_reading.html#data-transformations) for a recap if needed. Note, it would be best to create a new z-scored variable to then use within the model in this instance. 
:::



</div><p class="question-end"></p>





<div style="display:none;">




::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
# standardize scs score
scs_study <- 
  scs_study |> 
    mutate(
      zscs = (scs-mean(scs))/sd(scs)
    )
```
:::




</div><p class="solution-end"></p>



<br>



<div class='question-begin'>Question 5</div><div class='question-body'>



Fit your model (including the standardized predictor variables) using `lm()`, and assign it the name "dass_mdl".   

:::{.callout-tip appearance="simple" collapse="true"}

### Hint

We can fit interaction models using the `lm()` function.  

For an overview, see the [interaction models flashcards](https://uoepsy.github.io/dapr2/2526/labs/1_b3_reading.html#interaction-models).  

For an example, review the [interaction models > numeric x numeric example > model building flashcards](https://uoepsy.github.io/dapr2/2526/labs/1_b3_reading.html#numeric-x-numeric-example).

:::



</div><p class="question-end"></p>





<div style="display:none;">




::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
#fit interaction model
dass_mdl <- lm(dass ~  zn*zscs, data = scs_study)

#check model output
summary(dass_mdl)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```

